# PropFrame Video Worker — Environment Variables

Copy this to `.env.local` in the project root for development.

```env
# ─── Database ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:password@localhost:5432/propframe

# ─── Cloudflare R2 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
R2_ACCOUNT_ID=your-account-id
R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your-access-key-id
R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your-secret-access-key
R2_BUCKET=propframe-media
R2_PUBLIC_URL=https://your-public-url.r2.dev

# ─── Replicate (AI Video Generation) ─────────────────────────────────────────
REPLICATE_API_TOKEN=your-replicate-token

# ─── Redis (BullMQ Job Queue) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379

# ─── Worker Settings ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
WORKER_CONCURRENCY=2
WORKER_RATE_LIMIT=10
```

## Running Locally

```bash
# Terminal 1 — Start Redis
docker run -d -p 6379:6379 redis:7-alpine

# Terminal 2 — Start the video worker
cd workers/video-render
npm install
npm run dev
```

## CogVideoX Model

The worker uses `zsxkib/cogvideo-5b-filtered` on Replicate for image-to-video generation.
You can swap the model ID in `src/replicate.ts` to use a different version
(e.g. `THUDM/CogVideoX-5b` or a fine-tuned real estate variant once available).

## Production Deployment

```bash
cd workers/video-render
npm run build
npm start
```

For production, deploy the worker as a separate service on a GPU machine.
